Azure Fundamentals

Core Cloud Services

How does Azure work? 
 -Private and public cloud platform
 -Virtualization: Separate tight coupling between a computer's hardware and OS using an abstraction layer called a 'hypervisor'
 -Hypervisor emulates all the functions of a physical computer in a VM, each hypervisor can run multiple VMs
 -Repeat on a large scale in Microsoft datacenters globally
 -Each rack has many servers that each have a hypervisor
 -Network switch provides connectivity to each rack
 -Each rack has one server which runs a special piece of software called a 'fabric controller'
 -All of the fabric controllers are connected to another piece of software called the 'orchestrator'
 -Users make requests through the orchestrator's web API on the UI of the Azure portal, and the orchestrator then handles those requests
 
 Azure services:
  -Compute services
  -Cloud storage
  -Networking
  -App hosting
  -Artificial intelligence
  -Internet of Things (IoT)
  -Integration
  -Security
  
Compute services:
 -Azure VMs and Scale Sets
 -Azure Kubernetes: Management of a cluster of VMs that run containerized services
 -Azure Service Fabric: distributed systems platform
 -Azure Batch: Parallel and high-performance computing managed service
 -Azure Container Instances: containerized apps w/o provisioning servers or VMs
 -Azure Functions: event-driven, serverless compute function

